snippet.textDisplay:
Hi doctor Mike,

What is a good way of thanking a doctor that helped you on a flight :)

A few days ago I had to fly back home for about four hours (using two flights the first one being about an hour and the second about three hours or so) with a bruised back. I had asked the doctor that had diagnosed me if it was safe and recommended for me to fly home or not. He was fine with me flying back home because school asked us to leave before the corona virus reached the country we were staying in.

Also he kind of mentioned I was good at handeling pain and while he would normally not advice people to fly, he was confident I could handle it because I had managed to travel by bus for over 12 hours two days after bruising my back.

First flight was a piece of cake, I was totally fine. I can control my breathing and since I have done horsebackriding I learned to use an active way of sitting. With the painkillers and advice of the doctor I managed just fine.

Halfway through the second flight we got a lot of turbulence and because my back was sore from the landing the pain through the huge amount of painkillers was 10/10 and I passed out. After I regained my conciousness I luckily was able to tell my friends and get the flight attendants to help out. I knew I prefered not to pass out again. Especially since in the air it is hard to help people.

Flight attendents did not know what to do and a doctor noticed them trying to help out before she approached me and my friends. Being trained by my parents to stay calm no matter what situation and getting people to know the most important health things while travelling in a group, they managed to explain her what was going on with my back. Poor doctor tried keeping me awake and I really was like,' I am in too much pain to think, so if you want good answers don't ask me.' I was not exactly easy being really exhausted and half out of it. Luckily she knew acupuncture since I told her about the painkillers I was allowed to take and how I had taken them. Probably was her first time doing that in the air in mid flight. Had not been able to thank her though and feel quite bad about that. At least not as far as I remember.

snippet.textDisplay: I just finished studying infectious diseases and immunology in my Biology class, so I decided to do some reading on COVID-19. I've read different stories saying that COVID-19 can be spread to pets, and then there was a story that a dog had caught the virus. Soon after, different stories came out saying this was not true and there had been incorrect testing etc. On the website of Wageningen University and Research, it is stated that COVID-19 is a zoonotic disease and that it can therefore be transferred from animals to humans (and vice versa). However, on the Oregon Veterinary Medical Association website it is stated that "It is not believed that pets such as cats or dogs can pass COVID-19 to humans." Also, a lot of 'theories' of the origin of the virus state that it originated from a transfer of a bat or other animal (not necessarily through consumption) to a human. If the virus is zoonotic and the origin is thought to be passed from animal to human, how come people think it can not spread to pets? Maybe I misunderstood something, but I would really like to hear other people's thoughts.
